        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>An <strong>AR filter</strong> is a real-time visual effect overlaid on camera content using augmented reality. It uses face tracking, body tracking, or environmental detection to apply 3D objects, animations, or product try-ons through a phone camera on platforms like <strong>Instagram, Snapchat, and TikTok</strong>. Brands use AR filters for organic reach, product visualization, and interactive campaigns.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Daily AR users</div>
            <div class="tms-value">250M+ on Snap</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Social Media</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Engagement lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4x standard posts</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">AR filters combine brand exposure with interactive entertainment — two things social algorithms reward. Whether you are a cosmetics brand offering virtual lipstick try-ons or a local restaurant with a geotagged Snap Lens, the mechanics stay the same: real-time camera tracking, playful branded overlays, and organic sharing that costs nothing per impression.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is an AR filter?</h2>
        <p>An AR filter is a real-time visual overlay applied through a phone camera using augmented reality technology on social media platforms. It can be a face effect, background change, 3D object, color grading, or interactive animation. Snapchat pioneered them (calling them Lenses), and Instagram, TikTok, and Facebook quickly followed with their own AR filter ecosystems.</p>
        <p>Tools like Meta Spark AR Studio and Snap Lens Studio let anyone build custom filters, from simple color adjustments to complex face-morphing effects and 3D product try-ons. The marketing potential is real: Snap reports over 250 million Snapchat users interact with AR daily, and branded AR filters on Instagram generate an average of 500 million impressions per campaign for major brands.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Platform snapshot</div>
          <p>When people share content using your filter, your brand gets organic distribution at zero additional cost. Snap Inc. reports AR experiences see roughly <strong>4x higher engagement</strong> than standard social posts.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why AR filters matter</h2>
        <p>AR filters are one of the few formats where a small business can reach the same distribution ceiling as a large one. Four reasons they matter for marketers:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Organic virality.</strong> Users share AR content with friends, giving your brand free distribution without ad spend.</li>
          <li><strong>High engagement rates.</strong> AR experiences see 4x higher engagement than standard social posts, according to Snap Inc.</li>
          <li><strong>Product visualization.</strong> Beauty, eyewear, and furniture brands use AR try-ons to let customers preview products before purchasing.</li>
          <li><strong>Algorithm boost.</strong> Platform algorithms prioritize interactive content formats, including AR-enabled Stories and Reels.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>For local businesses and SMBs, custom AR filters offer a creative way to stand out on social without competing on ad budget. A dentist's perfect-smile filter or a restaurant's virtual-menu filter can drive local awareness at minimal cost.</p>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How AR filters work</h2>
        <p>AR filters rely on device cameras, computer vision, and real-time rendering. The pipeline runs 30 to 60 times per second so the overlay tracks with the user's movement without visible lag.</p>

        <h3>Face and body tracking</h3>
        <p>The phone camera detects facial landmarks (eyes, nose, mouth, jawline) or body pose in real time. The filter maps visual effects to these landmarks — a hat sits on the head, sunglasses align with the eyes, makeup appears on the skin. Tracking updates 30 to 60 times per second for smooth rendering.</p>

        <h3>Environmental detection</h3>
        <p>Some filters detect surfaces (floor, table, wall) and place 3D objects in the real world. A furniture brand's filter lets a customer see how a couch looks in their living room. An automotive brand places a virtual car in a driveway.</p>

        <h3>Creation tools</h3>
        <p>Meta Spark AR Studio (for Instagram and Facebook) and Snap Lens Studio (for Snapchat) are the primary creation platforms. Both are free. TikTok Effect House handles TikTok filters. No coding is required for basic effects, though advanced interactivity needs JavaScript knowledge.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Real AR filter examples</h2>
        <p>Three situations where AR filters produce measurable marketing outcomes:</p>

        <h3>1. Product launch</h3>
        <p>A cosmetics brand creates an Instagram AR filter that lets users virtually try on a new lipstick shade. The filter gets used 2.8 million times in the first week, generating organic reach equivalent to a $300K ad campaign.</p>

        <h3>2. Local business promotion</h3>
        <p>A pizza restaurant creates a Snapchat filter with a 3D pizza-hat animation, geotagged to their location. Customers who visit snap selfies with the filter and share with friends — free, hyper-local brand awareness.</p>

        <h3>3. Event engagement</h3>
        <p>A B2B company creates a custom AR filter for its annual conference. Attendees share filter content with the event hashtag, generating 15,000+ organic social posts. The filter becomes the unofficial conference branding, extending the event's reach far beyond attendees.</p>

