        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for AR filter campaigns</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Tie the filter to a specific action.</strong> A branded hashtag, a shareable moment, or a purchase intent — never a filter for its own sake.</li>
          <li><strong>Start with the platform your customer already uses.</strong> A Gen Z brand belongs on Snap or TikTok. A B2B conference belongs on Instagram Stories.</li>
          <li><strong>Design for the vertical screen first.</strong> Most AR is consumed one-handed, on 9:16 canvases. Test on a phone before signing off.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep the effect readable in one second.</strong> If a viewer cannot tell what the filter does before their thumb moves, they will not use it.</li>
          <li><strong>Instrument every share.</strong> Meta Spark and Snap Lens Studio both expose Impressions, Opens, Captures, and Shares — pull them into a dashboard the way you track any campaign.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh the filter every 6 to 8 weeks.</strong> AR fatigue is real. Sequels and seasonal variants keep the brand in rotation.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap</div>
          <p>Brands often ship a filter, then never promote it. A filter without a distribution push (creator seeding, paid Story units, hashtag challenge) rarely gets discovered organically. Budget for the distribution, not just the build.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common AR filter mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Building for the brand, not the user.</strong> If nothing about the filter is fun to share, no one will share it.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring platform review policies.</strong> Meta and Snap both reject filters that misrepresent size, alter faces in prohibited ways, or promote regulated products.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping localisation.</strong> A single English-only filter caps reach for international brands.</li>
          <li><strong>Under-testing on low-end devices.</strong> A filter that runs at 60fps on an iPhone 15 might stutter on a 3-year-old Android and never load for half your audience.</li>
          <li><strong>No CTA.</strong> Even a subtle end-card or bio link converts curiosity into a visit.</li>
        </ul>

